	<div id="content" class="hfeed">
			<article class="post-2114 post type-post status-publish hentry category-dealbook" id="post-2114">
                        <div class="visually-hidden">
                <span itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Morning Agenda: Bank of New York Mellon in Settlement</span>
                <span class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
                    By Sydney Ember                </span>
                <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-03-20T11:19:51+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">March 20, 2015 7:19 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">March 20, 2015 7:19 am</span>            </div>
			<div class="entry-content">
			<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//news.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/03/20/morning-agenda-bank-of-new-york-mellon-in-settlement/" data-title="Morning Agenda: Bank of New York Mellon in Settlement" data-description="Bank of New York Mellon will settle a currency trade case for $714 million. | Holcim and Lafarge say their merger is back on track. | The bar exam is under scrutiny. | S.E.C. chief sees virtue in activist investors.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="round-up">
<div class="ru-top-story">
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>BANK OF NEW YORK MELLON IN SETTLEMENT</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Federal and state authorities announced on Thursday that the Bank of New York Mellon would pay $714 million to settle accusations that it cheated government pension funds and other investors for more than a decade, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/03/20/business/dealbook/bank-of-new-york-mellon-to-pay-714-million-in-foreign-exchange-settlement.html?ref=dealbook">DealBookâs Ben Protess reports</a>. The settlement is part of a broader deal requiring the bank to dismiss some employees and overhaul its foreign exchange operation.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The settlement â which was struck with Preet Bharara, the United States attorney in Manhattan, and Eric T. Schneiderman, the New York attorney general â focuses on what the authorities called a â<b>fraudulent business model</b>â for the bankâs foreign exchange group. The bank had assured clients that they would enjoy a particular foreign exchange service âfree of chargeâ and would receive the best possible price when executing a currency trade. Instead, the authorities said, the bank did the opposite, imposing a âa substantial and undisclosed feeâ and providing clients âvirtually the worst rates.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The victims of the fraud were New York City pension funds and prominent private investors, the authorities said. City investors included teachers and police officers, while the private investment funds belonged to the likes of Duke University and the Walt Disney Company. The case against the Bank of New York Mellon is separate from a wider investigation into whether some of the worldâs biggest banks, including JPMorgan Chase and Citigroup, colluded to manipulate the foreign exchange market.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>CEMENT GIANTS REVIVE MERGER</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Holcim and Lafarge, the two European cement giants, said on Friday that they had broken a deadlock that threatened their merger plans and expressed confidence that they would close a deal this summer, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/03/21/business/dealbook/cement-giants-holcim-and-lafarge-say-merger-is-back-on.html?ref=dealbook">David Jolly reports in DealBook</a>.  The agreement, announced last year, had stumbled in recent weeks as Holcim shareholders complained that they were getting shortchanged in the supposed merger of equals. The companies had also begun to argue about who would lead the new group.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The companies said that they had solved those problems by revising the terms in a way that <b>sweetens the deal for Holcim shareholders</b> and agreeing that Bruno Lafont, the chief executive of Lafarge, would step aside and that another Lafarge executive would be named to the top job after the merger is finalized. Holcim and Lafarge are seeking a combination that would form the worldâs biggest cement and construction materials company. The companies had joint sales last year of around $33 billion and a total of about 131,000 employees worldwide.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>BAR EXAM UNDER FIRE</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The bar exam, a requirement in nearly every state for practicing law, is facing scrutiny from law school deans and some state legal establishments, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/03/20/business/dealbook/bar-exam-the-standard-to-become-a-lawyer-comes-under-fire.html?ref=dealbook">Elizabeth Olson writes in DealBook</a>. âSome states, including Arizona, Iowa and New Hampshire, are exploring or have adopted other options, questioning the wisdom of relying on a single written test as the gateway to legal practice,â she adds.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The debate, while not new, âbroke out in the open after the results of last summerâs exam were released in the fall, showing that the 51,005 test takers had the poorest results in nearly a decade,â Ms. Olson writes. âMany law school deans, bristling from criticism that they are replenishing their ranks with less academically qualified students as the number of law school applicants has fallen sharply, began to <b>openly question the mechanics of the bar exam</b>.â About 80 law school deans last November jointly asked for details on how test questions were chosen and scored.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ms. Olson adds: âEliminating or curtailing the current bar exam would <b>give law schools more leeway</b> to create programs and conduct testing that determines who becomes a lawyer. The schools say the examâs outsize importance forces them to devote more resources, including bar-specific courses, to prepare graduates for the crucial test rather than focusing on legal principles or hands-on law practice.â</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>ON THE AGENDA</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Friday is a â<b>quadruple witching</b>â day on Wall Street, meaning four types of contracts for futures and options will expire by dayâs end. This could mean unusually high trading volume, which could be positive for stocks. <b>Charles L. Evans</b>, president of the Chicago Fed, participates in a panel on risk management at 11:30 a.m. at the Brookings Institution.<br />
</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>S.E.C. CHIEF POSITIVE ON ACTIVISTS</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Mary Jo White, the chairwoman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, said in a speech at the Tulane Corporate Law Institute on Thursday that the agency did not necessarily look unkindly on activist investors, who buy stakes in companies and then push for changes in corporate strategy, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/03/20/business/dealbook/sec-chief-sees-virtue-in-activist-investors.html?ref=dealbook">DealBookâs Michael J. de la Merced writes</a>. Activist tactics, she said, âcan be compatible with the kind of engagement that I hope companies and shareholders can foster.â </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âOur role at the S.E.C. is not to determine whether activist campaigns are beneficial or detrimental in any given circumstance,â Ms. White said. âRather, the agencyâs central focus is making sure that shareholders are provided with the information they need and that all play by the rules.â<br />
</p>
</div>
